import numpy as np

# Extract all unique genres from 'listed_in'
genres = df['listed_in'].apply(lambda x: x.split(', '))
all_genres = np.unique([genre for sublist in genres for genre in sublist])

# Create a one-hot encoded DataFrame for genres
genre_df = pd.DataFrame(0, index=df.index, columns=all_genres)

for i, row in df.iterrows():
    for genre in row['listed_in'].split(', '):
        genre_df.at[i, genre] = 1

# Concatenate the new genre DataFrame with the original DataFrame
df = pd.concat([df, genre_df], axis=1)

# Drop the original 'listed_in' column
df.drop('listed_in', axis=1, inplace=True)

print("DataFrame after genre encoding and dropping 'listed_in':")
print(df.head())
print(df.shape)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Set plot style
sns.set_style("whitegrid")

# --- 1. Distribution of Movies vs. TV Shows ---
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
type_counts = df['type_num'].value_counts().sort_index()
type_labels = {0: 'TV Show', 1: 'Movie'}

sns.barplot(x=type_counts.index, y=type_counts.values, palette='viridis', hue=type_counts.index, legend=False)
plt.xticks(ticks=type_counts.index, labels=[type_labels[i] for i in type_counts.index])
plt.title('Distribution of Movies vs. TV Shows', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Content Type', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Titles', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

print("Generated bar plot for distribution of Movies vs. TV Shows.")

# --- 2. Top Genres Visualization ---
# Identify genre columns - they are present in the 'all_genres' variable from a previous step
genre_columns = [col for col in df.columns if col in all_genres]
genre_counts = df[genre_columns].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)

top_10_genres = genre_counts.head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.barplot(x=top_10_genres.values, y=top_10_genres.index, palette='magma')
plt.title('Top 10 Genres on Netflix', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Number of Titles', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Genre', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

print("Generated horizontal bar plot for top 10 genres.")

# --- 3. Content Release Trend over the Years ---
release_year_counts = df['release_year'].value_counts().sort_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
sns.lineplot(x=release_year_counts.index, y=release_year_counts.values, marker='o', color='teal')
plt.title('Number of Content Releases Per Year', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Release Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Titles', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print("Generated line plot for content release trend over the years.")

# --- 4. Distribution of Content Ratings ---
rating_counts = df['rating_code'].value_counts().sort_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x=rating_counts.index, y=rating_counts.values, palette='plasma', hue=rating_counts.index, legend=False)
plt.title('Distribution of Content Ratings (by code)', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Rating Code', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Titles', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

print("Generated bar plot for distribution of content ratings by code. (Original rating labels were not available after column drop).")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# 1. Identify and select relevant numerical features
# Original numerical columns
numerical_features = [
    'release_year', 'duration_num', 'type_num', 'rating_code', 'country_code', 'year_added'
]

# One-hot encoded genre columns (from 'all_genres' variable)
# Ensure 'all_genres' is defined from previous steps
if 'all_genres' in globals():
    genre_features = [col for col in df.columns if col in all_genres]
else:
    # Fallback if all_genres is not defined (should not happen if executed sequentially)
    print("Warning: 'all_genres' not found. Re-extracting genres.")
    genres = df['listed_in'].apply(lambda x: x.split(', '))
    all_genres = np.unique([genre for sublist in genres for genre in sublist])
    genre_features = [col for col in df.columns if col in all_genres]

# One-hot encoded duration_type columns
duration_type_features = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('duration_type_')]

# Combine all features for clustering
features_for_clustering = numerical_features + genre_features + duration_type_features

X = df[features_for_clustering]

print(f"Selected {len(features_for_clustering)} features for clustering.")
print("First 5 rows of selected features:")
print(X.head())

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Implement the Elbow Method
wcss = [] # Within-cluster sum of squares
k_range = range(1, 11) # Test for 1 to 10 clusters

for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10) # n_init is set to 10 to suppress warning
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the Elbow Method results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(k_range, wcss, marker='o', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal K', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS/Inertia)', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(k_range)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print("Generated Elbow Method plot to determine optimal number of clusters.")

optimal_k = 4 # Based on the Elbow Method plot, 4 appears to be a reasonable 'elbow' point

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

df['cluster_label'] = cluster_labels

# Prepare to analyze cluster characteristics
# For numerical features, calculate the mean
# For one-hot encoded features (genres and duration types), calculate the sum (to see count within cluster)

cluster_summary = df.groupby('cluster_label')[numerical_features].mean()

# For genre and duration type features, sum them up to see prevalence in each cluster
for col in genre_features + duration_type_features:
    cluster_summary[col] = df.groupby('cluster_label')[col].sum()

print(f"Cluster profiles for {optimal_k} clusters:")
print(cluster_summary)

plt.ylabel('Average Release Year', fontsize=12)

from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 5. Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# 6. Calculate R-squared score and Mean Squared Error
r_squared = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"R-squared Score: {r_squared:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error: {mse:.4f}")

# 8. Create a scatter plot and overlay the regression line
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.scatterplot(x=X_test['rating_code'], y=y_test, color='blue', label='Actual Durations', alpha=0.6)
sns.lineplot(x=X_test['rating_code'], y=y_pred, color='red', label='Regression Line', linewidth=2)
